# SOLID — Non-negotiable across backend + frontend

Apply to every function, class, Vue component, Pinia store, Elysia controller, use-case, and adapter. If a change violates one of these, call it out in your response before coding.

## S — Single Responsibility

One module = one reason to change. If a file mixes HTTP parsing, business rules, and SQL, split it.

```ts
// BAD: controller does validation + business + SQL
.delete('/:id', async ({ params, db }) => {
  if (!uuid(params.id)) throw 400;
  const row = await db.select()...;
  if (row.deletedAt) throw 404;
  await db.update(...).set({ deletedAt: new Date() });
})

// GOOD: controller → use-case → repository
.delete('/:id', async ({ params }) => {
  const { id } = folderIdParamSchema.parse(params);
  await services.softDeleteFolder.exec({ folderId: id });
})
```

## O — Open/Closed

Extend via new types/adapters, not by editing existing branches. Prefer a registry or strategy over a growing `switch`.

```ts
// BAD: every new extension edits this function
function iconFor(ext: string) {
  if (ext === '.pdf') return FileText;
  if (ext === '.csv') return FileSpreadsheet;
  // ...keeps growing
}

// GOOD: lookup table — new extensions are data, not code edits
const ICONS: Record<string, Icon> = { '.pdf': FileText, '.csv': FileSpreadsheet };
const iconFor = (ext: string) => ICONS[ext] ?? FileText;
```

## L — Liskov Substitution

Any implementation of a port must be swappable with no surprises. `NullCache` and `RedisCache` both honor the same contract (including `ping()` → `'ok' | 'down' | 'skipped'`). Never narrow pre-conditions or widen post-conditions in a subtype.

## I — Interface Segregation

Ports expose only what one caller needs. Don't bolt a `purge()` onto the `Cache` port because one script wants it — make a separate `CacheAdmin` port.

```ts
// BAD: every consumer drags along methods it never calls
interface Cache { get; set; ping; purge; rebuildIndex; exportSnapshot; }

// GOOD
interface Cache { get; set; invalidatePattern; ping; close; }
interface CacheAdmin extends Cache { purge; exportSnapshot; }
```

## D — Dependency Inversion

Use-cases/components depend on **ports / props / injected stores**, never on concrete adapters. Wiring happens at the edge (`src/container.ts`, `main.ts`, test harness).

```ts
// BAD: use-case imports Drizzle directly
import { db } from '../adapters/db/client';

// GOOD: use-case takes a FolderRepository port
export const softDeleteFolder = (repo: FolderRepository) => ({
  exec: ({ folderId }) => repo.softDelete(folderId),
});
```

## Quick self-check before you commit

1. Does this file have exactly one reason to change?
2. Can I add the next variant without editing existing branches?
3. Could I swap the implementation in a test without breaking callers?
4. Does the consumer see only the methods it actually uses?
5. Does this module import an abstraction, not a concrete adapter?

If any answer is "no", fix it now or surface the trade-off explicitly — don't let it rot.
